  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_608297244" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/608297244" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1569962-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546226581p2/1569962.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/608297244?book_show_action=true">May 06, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/1569962-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer608297244" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10544124465862036536">I first read The Oath just prior to its original release as a review copy. I remember being pretty blown away at the time. I had just read two of Peretti&apos;s &quot;Darkness&quot; novels which were well-done, and come off a disappointment in reading &quot;Prophet.&quot; This was, in my mind, Peretti&apos;s comeback. <br/><br/>It&apos;s been many years since I last read it, but I recently came across this paperback edition for $1 and couldn&apos;t pass it up. It remains a good novel in my view, and stands out among Peretti&apos;s best. <br/><br/>The story be</span>
  <span id="freeText10544124465862036536" style="display:none">I first read The Oath just prior to its original release as a review copy. I remember being pretty blown away at the time. I had just read two of Peretti's "Darkness" novels which were well-done, and come off a disappointment in reading "Prophet." This was, in my mind, Peretti's comeback. <br /><br />It's been many years since I last read it, but I recently came across this paperback edition for $1 and couldn't pass it up. It remains a good novel in my view, and stands out among Peretti's best. <br /><br />The story begins with a terrifying chase through a dark forest. A man has just been brutally killed, possibly eaten, in a truly horrific attack in the Pacific Northwest wild. His brother, a wildlife biologist, investigates the attack with a local sheriff's deputy. Both of them come up against the strange beliefs and superstitions of the people inhabiting the nearby town of Hyde River. Steve, the biologist, insists on getting to the truth of how and why his brother died, but unexpectedly finds himself fighting battles on every possible front as he realizes the creature who attacked is now after him.<br /><br />The book is almost as enjoyable as it was the first time I read. It no longer takes my breath away, but how many books can do that after you already know what's coming next? The only real criticism I have is that its allegory is far, far too obvious in its symbolism. In this edition, Peretti spells it out in the preface - this is what my book is all about.<br /><br />Shouldn't the reader be able to decide that for themselves? Are readers so stupid that they won't understand what Peretti is trying to say through the story? <br /><br />This is the big problem I have with Christian fiction by evangelicals. The focus is on the message, not the story itself - where an art form is concerned, that approach is exactly backwards. <br /><br />To Peretti's credit, he later co-wrote "House" with Ted Dekker, which dealt with similar themes but without the sermonizing to weaken an otherwise very strong story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10544124465862036536" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review608297244">
